reviews.text: I have really enjoyed playing this game. it is challenging and very entertaining. My kids have played it and and we talk about the logic and thoughts necessary to complete the different puzzles. very fun!
reviews.title: Very fun and challenging

reviews.text: As other reviewers have noted, the CrossMe puzzles are real nonograms where the pattern is the picture (I've gone through the BW and color versions twice). The FlipPix puzzles are fairly random patterns that don't let you see what is being created until it's solved. The interface for marking tiles is good.
reviews.title: Not too hard

reviews.text: This was a featured app for free and I'm so glad I took a chance. It is so much fun and it can be addicting. It's a great problem solving game as it does require you to put on your thinking cap. Once you get it, you've got it! So go for it!
reviews.title: Addicting

reviews.text: Great game. Once you start getting to 15x15, it starts getting a little annoying visually. They combat that by being able to zoom out, but then it's a little hard to tap precisely. Other than that, super fun. I just keep doing one puzzle after another.
reviews.title: HTC EVO

reviews.text: Has many levels and pictures to solve. If you like playing with numbers, like sudoko puzzles you will like this. Wildlifeart from different area around the globe.
reviews.title: Lots of fun to keep you thinking

reviews.text: I like the concept of this game. At first I thought it was going to be like a jigsaw puzzle but it has grown on me.
reviews.title: Interesting

reviews.text: Love this game! Excellent faotd, well worth it even at regular price.Four stars because the squares are way too small to play level 20 on the kindle.
reviews.title: great brain exercise

reviews.text: I got this game for free, so wasn't expecting much. It has turned out to be one of my favorites. I like that you can start easy to learn it and then rework it at a harder level. Nice change from suduko.
reviews.title: Love it

reviews.text: Am really enjoying this app. Love the different levels of difficulty and also how you have to use your brain to reason it out. Fun.
reviews.title: FlipPix Art - Wildlife

reviews.text: very simple to understand, good tutorial, beginners to advanced levels. love this game. it has nothing fancy in graphics, but gameplay is good
reviews.title: excellent game, very interesting

reviews.text: Not a bad card game for killing some time. Game could be made better if you could increase the degree of difficulty say advanced or beginner selections. Very frustrating when your partner plays the wrong card when they no longer have trumps.Game could stand some improvement.
reviews.title: Whist needs improvement

reviews.text: This is such fun!!!! If you already know how to play the game you will enjoy it. However, if you are learning ... this is a great way to learn the dynamics of the game. Once you have it down, try Bid Whist and perfect your bidding skills...most of all, enjoy!
reviews.title: such fun!

reviews.text: I like tis game because you can play anytime you want to. If you like to play with your friends and family then this is the game for you.
reviews.title: instant friends

reviews.text: Compared to apps produced by AI, the graphics and options are very limited with this card game. However, the game plays as intended with no hangups of glitches. The unfortunate part is that it gets monotonous quickly.
reviews.title: Very basic...

reviews.text: out of several hearts games that I tried for android, this one has the best graphics and the most convenient interface (e.g. picking a card out of the hand etc is a no brainer, while in other games it's been done really not that well) plus it has a nice tutorial. This is simply a really nicely done game - one of two best hearts games I've tried.If You are looking for smarter computer opponents , I would advise You to try Hearts free by AI factory limited - it has a better artificial inteligence engine (that's about how well your computer opponents can play) and a graphical interface at least same neat as this game, but ... the way the cards are displayed in your hand is worse and really not too clever, resulting in selecting of the cards from Your hand being sometimes simply a painful process - I mean: you try to touch/select a certain card and another one gets selected instead... - seriously something that could be improved. But I still choose it over this one due to opponents' level, plus there's the undo option, so if you wanna learn it can be useful.oh, and one more thing:I've read several reviews complaining about lots of ads within this game, interrupting the play etc. I tell You what: I played this game a lot, and have not seen/encountered one single ad. And here is why: you know, it's always good to know, what You are doing and be aware how the device that you are using works ... So here is a simple trick for all you complaining ones:you want no advertisements Turn off data transmission/internet connection (wi-fi mobile network data transmission) before you launch the game and keep it turned off while the game is on.That's it - and You'll have no ads in the game.And this simple trick applies not only to this game but to all the games that display ads.These ads are being downloaded by applications while these apps are on. So you cut out the downloading possibilities, and there will be no ads downloaded and thus no ads displayed.But if You already see the ads, then close that app, clear that app's cache (in application manager) - once in aplication manager I suggest forcing the stop of the app and then clearing its cache - and then before you launch the app again, make sure you have all ways of data transmission turned off/disabled and launch the app and enjoy it with no advertisements :)- Your welcome -)

reviews.text: The European War games have progressed since the crude and dull original. The first was set in Napoleonic times and very much a Risk clone, can't say anything about European War 2 (WW2) , but European War 3 covers more original ground with a World War 1 setting.The gameplay owes much to Axis Allies. EW3 is attractive with clean maps and interface, with nicely rendered unit icons evocative of the period. The essence of it remains simple, conquer every last enemy province. But the card system adds some depth and forces the player to make decisions as to how to allocate the turn's income: develop infrastructure, buy new units, upgrade those you have or play tactical cards Your choice. You can also choose which medals to buy or raise your command rating.Of course, there's room for improvement. The translations to English can be comically bad and while there's a tutorial, things remain unexplained. For example, you have infantry, cavalry, machine guns, artillery, (and for certain countries) tanks, as well as battleships, cruisers, destroyers and transports at sea. These are rated numerically on the battle animation screens but nowhere does it explain what these numbers mean or how one is better than others in attack or defense. Pay attention to the hints during load times, they do offer some info not found elsewhere.Also there are no mission objectives or time limits. Once you gain the upper hand and the balance of income swings ever more increasingly in your favor, the outcome becomes a forgone conclusion, with the end game a mopping up operation. But while things hang in the balance it's good fun and the AI makes a decent sparring partner. There's a number of scenarios in each campaign which you can play as various global powers, although sticklers for accuracy may be irritated by the casual treatment of history in certain scenarios and quirks such as infantry being able to damage warships.Well worth the 99 cents if you enjoy a casual, beer pretzels style of wargame. There's an unobtrusive and half-hearted stab at IAP but you can win without spending any extra money.
